{{see|ΕΑΜ}}
==Old English==
===Etymology===
From a Germanic compound ''*awa-heima-'', from ''*awa-'' (Old Norse [[afi]] ‘grandfather’, Gothic [[𐌰𐍅𐍉]] ‘grandmother’; cognate with Latin [[avus]] ‘grandfather’, [[avunculus]] ‘uncle’, Russian [[вуй]] ‘uncle’; all from Indo-European ''*awos'' ‘maternal grandfather’) + ''*heimaz'' ‘intimate, close’.  The word is cognate with Old Frisian [[em|ēm]], Middle Dutch [[om|ōm]] (Dutch [[oom]]), Old High German [[oheim]] (German [[Oheim]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /æ:am/

===Noun===
'''ēam''' ''m''
# an [[uncle]], especially on the mother’s side

===Descendents===
*English [[eme]]


